snippet.textDisplay:
Hey! Hope you see this, I'm a baker and would love to give you tips on improving the bread.

The dough has to be wetter than that, just keep adding water, it won't affect the end product if the recipe says only so much, if anything it would be better! The wetter the dough, the better and if you keep it on the Kitchen Aid for about 15 minutes full speed it'll come together. But not so wet that you cant pick it up. It should stick to the work top but not leave any dough residue (if that makes sense...).

Also, I advise a double prove so make the dough, put it in and oiled bowl, covered in a warm spot for an hour. Then carefully shaping it/ putting it into the tin and covering it and proving again for 15 minutes then bake. You had the issue with the denseness because the yeast couldn't activate with the dough being so heavy :( hopefully these tips will help you when you next try this!!!

If I think of anything else I'll tell more baker's secrets
Stay safe x
snippet.textOriginal:
Hey! Hope you see this, I'm a baker and would love to give you tips on improving the bread.

The dough has to be wetter than that, just keep adding water, it won't affect the end product if the recipe says only so much, if anything it would be better! The wetter the dough, the better and if you keep it on the Kitchen Aid for about 15 minutes full speed it'll come together. But not so wet that you cant pick it up. It should stick to the work top but not leave any dough residue (if that makes sense...).

Also, I advise a double prove so make the dough, put it in and oiled bowl, covered in a warm spot for an hour. Then carefully shaping it/ putting it into the tin and covering it and proving again for 15 minutes then bake. You had the issue with the denseness because the yeast couldn't activate with the dough being so heavy :( hopefully these tips will help you when you next try this!!!

If I think of anything else I'll tell more baker's secrets
Stay safe x

snippet.textDisplay: i just want to say thank you guys, the past week has had been on edge as I am not able to work from home and my job is considered an essential service - especially right now - as i work for the railroad which keeps supply chains operating. So i continue to work, in a truck with different people coming in and out of it and have to stay in hotels where i usually cross paths people who just got off flights and are checking in. Ive had to ask the hotel staff not to send housekeeping to my room during the stay in the event they had picked it up from another guest. having something to watch that isnt about the world right now is kind of relaxing. as much as i want to delete my social media and stop watching the news i have to stay informed to protect myself, and finding breaks isnt easy. So thank you, your content is very much needed right now and continuing to produce it isnt insensitive, its essential. stay safe
